Chapter 8 – Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)¶

Historical Background

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) was first introduced by Ronald A. Fisher (1936) as a statistical method for classifying observations into distinct categories. Fisher’s original work focused on two-class problems, demonstrating how linear combinations of variables could optimally separate different populations. Later, in 1948, C.R. Rao extended Fisher’s approach to handle multiple classes, leading to what is now called Multi-class Linear Discriminant Analysis (MLDA) or Multiple Discriminant Analysis (MDA).

Concept and Purpose

LDA is a supervised learning method that serves both as a classification technique and a dimensionality reduction method.

The main goal of LDA is to:

Project high-dimensional data onto a lower-dimensional subspace that maximizes class separability — preserving differences between classes while minimizing variation within each class.

This projection enables:

  • Better class discrimination for visualization and prediction.
  • Reduced computational cost in lower-dimensional spaces.
  • Noise reduction, since LDA focuses on the most discriminative directions.

Mathematical Foundation LDA finds projection directions $w$ that maximize the ratio of between-class to within-class variance:

$$ \hat{w} = \arg\max_{w} \frac{w^T S_b w}{w^T S_w w} $$

where

  • $S_w$: Within-class scatter matrix
    $$ S_w = \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{x_i \in C_k} (x_i - \mu_k)(x_i - \mu_k)^T $$
  • $S_b$: Between-class scatter matrix
    $$ S_b = \sum_{k=1}^{K} n_k (\mu_k - \mu)(\mu_k - \mu)^T $$

with

  • $\mu_k$: mean vector of class $k$
  • $\mu$: overall mean vector
  • $n_k$: number of observations in class $k$

The discriminant directions are obtained from the eigenvectors of $S_w^{-1} S_b$ associated with the largest eigenvalues. We adjust the angle so that: The shadows of different classes are as far apart as possible The shadows of points in the same class are as tight as possible We want a projection direction that: Stretches the space between classes Compresses the space within each class

Probabilistic Model and Decision Rule

Assume each class $k$ follows a multivariate normal (Gaussian) distribution:

$$ f_k(\mathbf{x}) = \frac{1}{(2\pi)^{p/2}|\Sigma_k|^{1/2}} \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{x}-\boldsymbol{\mu}_k)^\top \Sigma_k^{-1}(\mathbf{x}-\boldsymbol{\mu}_k)\right) $$
  • LDA assumption: $\Sigma_k = \Sigma$ for all $k$
  • QDA assumption: $\Sigma_k$ may differ across classes

Let $\pi_k$ denote the prior probability of class $k$.
Then, the discriminant function for class $k$ is:

$$ \delta_k(\mathbf{x}) = \mathbf{x}^\top \Sigma^{-1}\boldsymbol{\mu}_k -\frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{\mu}_k^\top\Sigma^{-1}\boldsymbol{\mu}_k +\log(\pi_k) $$

A new observation $\mathbf{x}$ is assigned to the class with the highest discriminant score:

$$ \widehat{f}(\mathbf{x}) = \arg\max_k \, \delta_k(\mathbf{x}) $$

Linear Decision Boundaries

For two classes $k$ and $l$, the decision boundary satisfies:

$$ \mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{w}_k + b_k = \mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{w}_l + b_l $$

Simplifying, we obtain the linear boundary equation:

$$ \mathbf{x}^\top (\mathbf{w}_k - \mathbf{w}_l) + (b_k - b_l) = 0 $$

This defines a hyperplane separating the classes.

  • The normal vector $(\mathbf{w}_k - \mathbf{w}_l)$ determines the orientation.
  • The intercept $(b_k - b_l)$ determines the offset.

Assumptions¶

  • Multivariate normality within each class
  • Equal covariance matrices across classes
  • Adequate sample size per class to estimate means/covariances

Extensions and Related Methods

  • Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA): Allows class-specific covariance matrices → quadratic boundaries.
  • Regularized Discriminant Analysis (RDA): Shrinks class covariances toward a pooled or diagonal matrix for stability in small samples.
  • Kernel Discriminant Analysis: Projects data into a higher-dimensional space to capture nonlinear class boundaries.

These are the average measurements for each species: Setosa has small petals and relatively wide sepals. Versicolor is intermediate in all dimensions. Virginica has the largest petals and sepals overall. These mean differences already suggest good separation, especially in petal measurements.

Coefficients of linear discriminants There are 3 classes - LD1 , LD2 (2 linear transformations)

$LD1 = 0.8293776 \times Sepal.Length + 1.5344731 \times Sepal.Width + ... -2.8104603 \times Petal.Width $

Proportion of trace:¶

These proportions of the eigenvalues are associated with the LDs, and are always in descending order (LD1 > LD2 > ... > LD3 > …), which sum to 1. The first LD is the important for discriminating between the groups, and LD3 is least important of these three.

In [7]:
library(ggplot2)
#predict(fit) applies the LDA model to get predicted classes and discriminant scores. pred$x gives the new coordinates in the LDA space (LD1 & LD2).
pred = predict(fit)
scores = as.data.frame(pred$x)           # Extracts just the LDA scores (LD1 and LD2) and puts them into a DataFrame.
scores$Species = iris$Species            # change iris -> dat if scaled, Extracts just the LDA scores (LD1 and LD2) and puts them into a DataFrame.

eig = fit$svd^2
prop_trace = eig / sum(eig)
prop_ld1 = sprintf("LD1 (%.1f%%)", 100 * prop_trace[1])
prop_ld2 = sprintf("LD2 (%.1f%%)", 100 * prop_trace[2])


p = ggplot(scores, aes(x = LD1, y = LD2, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.9) +
  stat_ellipse(level = 0.68, linewidth = 0.7) +   # ellipse ~ 1 SD
  labs(title = "LDA Scatter Plot: LD1 vs LD2 (iris data)",
       x = prop_ld1, y = prop_ld2) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13) +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

print(p)

Applications of LDA¶

  1. Face Recognition
    In computer vision, LDA is widely used for face recognition. Each face is represented by a large number of pixel values. LDA is applied to reduce the dimensionality of these features, making the classification process more manageable. The resulting new dimensions are linear combinations of pixel values, called Fisher’s faces, which form templates used for classification.

  2. Medical Diagnosis
    LDA is used to classify patients' disease states (e.g., mild, moderate, or severe) based on various medical parameters and ongoing treatments. This helps doctors adjust their treatment plans based on the severity of the condition.

  3. Customer Identification
    In marketing, LDA can be used to identify customers who are most likely to purchase a specific product. By conducting surveys, features describing customer preferences are collected, and LDA is applied to select the key factors that distinguish potential buyers, aiding targeted marketing strategies.

Example: A hospital uses Linear Discriminant Analysis to classify patients as Diabetic or Non-Diabetic based on age, glucose level, BMI, and blood pressure.¶

Pima.tr contains medical and demographic measurements from adult female patients of Pima Indian heritage. The goal is to predict whether a patient has diabetes based on clinical predictors.

Variable Description
npreg Number of pregnancies
glu Plasma glucose concentration (2-hours post glucose challenge)
bp Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)
skin Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)
bmi Body mass index (weight/height²)
ped Diabetes pedigree function (family history index)
age Age in years
type Outcome: "Yes" (diabetes) or "No" (no diabetes)
